**Sec. 10101. Re-evaluation of Thrifty Food Plan.**

This section amends the Food and Nutrition Act of 2008 to redefine the "thrifty food plan," which is used to determine SNAP benefits. It specifies that the plan must be based on the 2021 report by the Department of Agriculture and sets conditions for future updates. The cost of the plan will be adjusted annually based on the Consumer Price Index starting in 2025. Additionally, it establishes specific household adjustment ratios for different family sizes and allows cost adjustments for Hawaii, Alaska, Guam, and the Virgin Islands.

**Sec. 10102. Modifications to SNAP Work Requirements for Able-Bodied Adults.**

This section modifies SNAP work requirements for able-bodied adults without dependents. It expands the list of exceptions to these requirements, including individuals under 18 or over 65, those medically unfit for employment, pregnant women, and members of certain Native American groups. It also standardizes enforcement by setting specific unemployment rate thresholds for noncontiguous states and allows for exemptions for these states if they demonstrate good faith efforts to comply with the requirements.

**Sec. 10103. Availability of Standard Utility Allowances Based on Receipt of Energy Assistance.**

This section amends the Food and Nutrition Act of 2008 to allow the use of standard utility allowances for households receiving energy assistance, with a specific focus on households that include elderly or disabled members. It also clarifies the treatment of third-party energy assistance payments for households with and without elderly or disabled members.

**Sec. 10104. Restrictions on Internet Expenses.**

This section amends the Food and Nutrition Act of 2008 to prohibit the use of service fees associated with internet connection in computing the excess shelter expense deduction for SNAP benefits. This change aims to limit the use of internet expenses in determining SNAP eligibility and benefits.

**Sec. 10105. Matching Funds Requirements.**

This section introduces a new state quality control incentive program for SNAP. It establishes a sliding scale of federal funding based on the state's payment error rate, with states receiving a higher federal share if their error rate is lower. The program phases in starting in 2028, with adjustments for states with high error rates. It also sets a maximum federal payment for the cost of an allotment.

**Sec. 10106. Administrative Cost Sharing.**

This section amends the Food and Nutrition Act of 2008 to reduce the federal share of administrative costs for SNAP from 50% to 25% starting in 2027. The federal share will remain at 50% through 2026.

**Sec. 10107. National Education and Obesity Prevention Grant Program.**

This section extends the authorization for the National Education and Obesity Prevention Grant Program through 2025. The program provides grants to states and local educational agencies to support nutrition education and obesity prevention activities.

**Sec. 10108. Alien SNAP Eligibility.**

This section amends the Food and Nutrition Act of 2008 to restrict SNAP eligibility for aliens. It requires individuals to be residents of the United States and either U.S. citizens or nationals, lawfully admitted permanent residents, or certain other eligible aliens, such as those granted Cuban and Haitian entrant status or those residing under a Compact of Free Association. The income and financial resources of ineligible individuals will still be considered in determining the eligibility and value of the allotment for the household.

**Sec. 10201. Rescission of Amounts for Forestry.**

This section rescinds unobligated balances of funds appropriated for forestry programs under the Agricultural Act of 2014. The rescinded funds are from specific sections of the Act, including paragraphs 23001(a)(3) and (4), 23002(a)(1) through (4), 23003(a)(2), and 23005.

**Sec. 10301. Effective Reference Price; Reference Price.**

This section amends the Agricultural Act of 2014 to adjust the reference prices for various covered commodities, effective for the 2025 crop year. It sets specific reference prices for commodities like wheat, corn, soybeans, and others, and establishes a formula for annual adjustments starting in 2031. The maximum reference price for each commodity is also set at 113% of the initial 2025 price.

**Sec. 10302. Base Acres.**

This section amends the Agricultural Act of 2014 to extend the deadline for allocating base acres to eligible farms from 2023 to 2031. It also provides for an additional allocation of up to 30 million base acres to eligible farms, with the option for owners to opt out. The eligibility criteria for receiving additional base acres are based on a 5-year average of planted acreage and natural disaster losses.

**Sec. 10303. Producer Election.**

This section amends the Agricultural Act of 2014 to extend the deadline for producers to elect between Price Loss Coverage (PLC) and Agriculture Risk Coverage (ARC) programs from 2023 to 2031. It also requires the Secretary to make the higher of PLC or ARC payments for the 2025 crop year. Additionally, it modifies the Federal Crop Insurance Supplemental Coverage Option to apply to acres rather than specific crops.

**Sec. 10304. Price Loss Coverage.**

This section amends the Agricultural Act of 2014 to extend the deadlines for various provisions related to Price Loss Coverage (PLC) from 2023 to 2031. It also adjusts the reference prices and payment rates for PLC payments to align with the new reference prices established in Sec. 10301.

**Sec. 10305. Agriculture Risk Coverage.**

This section amends the Agricultural Act of 2014 to extend the deadlines for various provisions related to Agriculture Risk Coverage (ARC) from 2023 to 2031. It also adjusts the revenue coverage levels for ARC from 85% to 90% for the 2014 through 2024 crop years and from 85% to 90% for the 2025 through 2031 crop years.

**Sec. 10306. Equitable Treatment of Certain Entities.**

This section amends the Food Security Act of 1985 to expand the definition of "qualified pass-through entity" to include partnerships, S corporations, limited liability companies, joint ventures, and general partnerships. It also modifies provisions related to attribution of payments, persons actively engaged in farming, joint and several liability, and exclusion from Adjusted Gross Income (AGI) calculation to include these entities.

**Sec. 10307. Payment Limitations.**

This section amends the Food Security Act of 1985 to increase the payment limitations for direct and counter-cyclical payments from $125,000 to $155,000. It also establishes an annual inflation adjustment for these limits based on the Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers, starting in 2025.

**Sec. 10308. Adjusted Gross Income Limitation.**

This section amends the Food Security Act of 1985 to add an exception to the adjusted gross income (AGI) limitation for certain operations. It allows individuals or legal entities to exceed the AGI limit if at least 75% of their average gross income derives from farming, ranching, or silviculture activities, including agri-tourism and direct-to-consumer marketing.

**Sec. 10309. Marketing Loans.**

This section amends the Agricultural Act of 2014 to extend the availability of nonrecourse marketing assistance loans for loan commodities from 2023 to 2031. It also sets specific loan rates for various commodities for the 2026 through 2031 crop years, adjusting the rates for cotton storage costs, and extends the availability of loan deficiency payments and special competitive provisions for extra long staple cotton.

**Sec. 10310. Repayment of Marketing Loans.**

This section amends the Agricultural Act of 2014 to modify the repayment rates for marketing loans. It sets the repayment rate for upland cotton at the prevailing world market price, with a refund for the lowest price during a 30-day period after repayment. It also adjusts the repayment rates for other commodities to the lesser of the loan rate or the prevailing world market price.

**Sec. 10311. Economic Adjustment Assistance for Textile Mills.**

This section amends the Agricultural Act of 2014 to increase the value of economic adjustment assistance for textile mills from 3 cents per pound to 5 cents per pound starting in 2025.

**Sec. 10312. Sugar Program Updates.**

This section amends the Federal Agriculture Improvement and Reform Act of 1996 to update loan rates and commodity credit corporation storage rates for sugar. It also modernizes beet sugar allotments, reallocates tariff-rate quota shortfalls, and studies refined sugar imports.

**Sec. 10313. Dairy Policy Updates.**

This section amends the Agricultural Act of 2014 to update dairy margin coverage production history, increase the maximum coverage level from 5 million to 6 million pounds, and adjust premium discounts for dairy margin coverage. It also extends the duration of the program from 2025 to 2031.

**Sec. 10314. Implementation.**

This section provides additional funding for the implementation of subtitle C of the Act, allocating $50 million for various activities, including mandatory surveys of dairy production cost and product yield information, and a study on refined sugar imports.

**Sec. 10401. Supplemental Agricultural Disaster Assistance.**

This section amends the Agricultural Act of 2014 to update livestock indemnity payments, livestock forage disaster program, emergency assistance for livestock, honey bees, and farm-raised fish, and the tree assistance program. It increases payment rates, extends eligibility periods, and adds new provisions for unborn livestock death losses and assistance for losses due to bird depredation.

**Sec. 10501. Beginning Farmer and Rancher Benefit.**

This section amends the Federal Crop Insurance Act to extend the definition of a "beginning farmer or rancher" from 5 years to 10 years. It also increases premium assistance for beginning farmers and ranchers, providing additional support for the first four years of participation in crop insurance programs.

**Sec. 10502. Area-Based Crop Insurance Coverage and Affordability.**

This section amends the Federal Crop Insurance Act to increase the maximum coverage level for area-based crop insurance from 85% to 95% and the premium subsidy from 65% to 80%. It also modifies the premium rate for catastrophic risk protection.

**Sec. 10503. Administrative and Operating Expense Adjustments.**

This section amends the Federal Crop Insurance Act to provide additional administrative and operating expense subsidies for approved insurance providers, including adjustments for inflation and specialty crops. It also establishes a pilot program for poultry insurance to cover extreme weather-related risks.

**Sec. 10504. Premium Support.**

This section amends the Federal Crop Insurance Act to increase the premium support levels for various coverage levels, including individual yield or revenue coverage, individual yield or revenue coverage aggregated across multiple commodities, and area yield or revenue coverage.

**Sec. 10505. Program Compliance and Integrity.**

This section amends the Federal Crop Insurance Act to increase the funding for program compliance and integrity activities from $4 million to $6 million for fiscal years 2014 through 2025, and to $10 million for fiscal year 2026 and thereafter.

**Sec. 10506. Reviews, Compliance, and Integrity.**

This section amends the Federal Crop Insurance Act to increase the funding for reviews, compliance, and integrity activities from $4 million to $6 million for fiscal years 2014 through 2025, and to $10 million for fiscal year 2026 and thereafter.

**Sec. 10507. Poultry Insurance Pilot Program.**

This section amends the Federal Crop Insurance Act to establish a pilot program for index-based insurance for contract poultry growers, including broilers and laying hens, to cover extreme weather-related risks associated with increased utility costs.

**Sec. 10601. Conservation.**

This section amends the Food Security Act of 1985 to increase funding for conservation programs, including the Conservation Reserve Program, Conservation Stewardship Program, and Regional Conservation Partnership Program. It also extends the Grassroots Source Water Protection Program and the Voluntary Public Access and Habitat Incentive Program.

**Sec. 10602. Supplemental Agricultural Trade Promotion Program.**

This section establishes a new program to encourage the accessibility, development, maintenance, and expansion of commercial export markets for U.S. agricultural commodities. It provides $285 million in funding for fiscal year 2027 and each subsequent fiscal year.

**Sec. 10603. Nutrition.**

This section amends the Emergency Food Assistance Act of 1983 to extend the authorization for the Emergency Food Assistance Program through 2031.

**Sec. 10604. Research.**

This section amends various agricultural research and education programs to increase funding and extend authorization periods. It includes the Urban, Indoor, and Other Emerging Agricultural Production Research, Education, and Extension Initiative, the Foundation for Food and Agriculture Research, the Scholarships for Students at 1890 Institutions, the Assistive Technology Program for Farmers With Disabilities, the Specialty Crop Research Initiative, and the Research Facilities Act.

**Sec. 10605. Energy.**

This section amends the Farm Security and Rural Investment Act of 2002 to extend the authorization for the Renewable Energy for America Program through 2031.

**Sec. 10606. Horticulture.**

This section amends various horticulture programs to increase funding and extend authorization periods. It includes the Plant Pest and Disease Management and Disaster Prevention Program, the Specialty Crop Block Grants Program, the Organic Production and Market Data Initiative, the Modernization and Improvement of International Trade Technology Systems and Data Collection, the National Organic Certification Cost-share Program, and the Multiple Crop and Pesticide Use Survey.

**Sec. 10607. Miscellaneous.**

This section includes various miscellaneous provisions, such as the Animal Disease Prevention and Management Program, the Sheep Production and Marketing Grant Program, the Pima Agriculture Cotton Trust Fund, the Agriculture Wool Apparel Manufacturers Trust Fund, the Wool Research and Promotion Program, the Emergency Citrus Disease Research and Development Trust Fund, and other related programs. It extends authorization periods, increases funding, and makes other adjustments to these programs. [end of text]


